<subSubSection id="D9BC651EFF98FF99D495E340548B1929" box="[199,969,1303,1328]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="91193695FF98FF99D495E340548B1929" blockId="68.[151,1437,151,1653]" box="[199,969,1303,1328]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FF98FF99D495E340560C1936" bold="true" box="[199,334,1303,1328]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Etymology.</emphasis>
Species named after its dark-coloured major body setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D9BC651EFF98FF99D495E36B52501A73" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="91193695FF98FF99D495E36B52501A73" blockId="68.[151,1437,151,1653]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FF98FF99D495E36B560D1953" bold="true" box="[199,335,1340,1365]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Comments.</emphasis>
One of the unusual traits of this species is the pelta with very irregular lateral margins, which are frequently eroded and curved (
<figureCitation id="099D2A10FF98FF99D659E3085537197E" box="[523,629,1375,1400]" captionStart="FIGURES 191–197" captionStartId="67.[151,264,1972,1995]" captionTargetBox="[192,1398,193,1957]" captionTargetId="figure@67.[192,1398,193,1957]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="FIGURES 191–197. Holopothrips nigrisetis sp. nov. paratypes. (191) body; (192) head and pronotum; (193) mesonotum; (194) pelta; (195) spermatheca; (196) pore plates on abdominal sternites VII–VIII; (197) metanotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445236/files/figure.png" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Fig. 194</figureCitation>
). The margins of the male pore plates are also irregular, with the anteroangular plates on sternite VIII frequently being linked to the posterior plate near the lateral margins (
<figureCitation id="099D2A10FF98FF99D13DE3D3578719C6" captionStart="FIGURES 191–197" captionStartId="67.[151,264,1972,1995]" captionTargetBox="[192,1398,193,1957]" captionTargetId="figure@67.[192,1398,193,1957]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="FIGURES 191–197. Holopothrips nigrisetis sp. nov. paratypes. (191) body; (192) head and pronotum; (193) mesonotum; (194) pelta; (195) spermatheca; (196) pore plates on abdominal sternites VII–VIII; (197) metanotum." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1445236/files/figure.png" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Fig. 196</figureCitation>
). On sternite VII of some specimens it is unclear if the anteroangular plates are absent or reduced to small spots linked to the posterior plate. 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FF98FF99D58BE39B559F19E2" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[473,733,1484,1509]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrisetis">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FF98FF99D58BE39B559F19E2" box="[473,733,1484,1509]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Holopothrips nigrisetis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may be related to some other large, dark-bodied species of the genus with two pairs of epimeral setae, such as 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FF98FF99D689E3A654331A0E" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[731,881,1519,1544]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="atlanticus">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FF98FF99D689E3A654331A0E" box="[731,881,1519,1544]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">H. atlanticus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(which has pronotal am and coxal setae welldeveloped and longer than aa setae, and pore plates only on sternite VIII), 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FF98FF99D7B0E04253241A2B" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[994,1126,1556,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cardosoi">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FF98FF99D7B0E04253241A2B" box="[994,1126,1556,1581]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">H. cardosoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="56A64D16FF98FF99D0CCE04252501A2A" authority="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri, 2018" authorityName="Lindner &amp; Ferrari &amp; Mound &amp; Cavalleri" authorityYear="2018" box="[1182,1298,1557,1580]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Holopothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nigrum" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FF98FF99D0CCE04252501A2A" box="[1182,1298,1557,1580]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">H. nigrum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="B8E157FCFF98FF99D14BE043521B1A2B" box="[1305,1369,1556,1581]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" rank="species">
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FF98FF99D14BE043521B1A2B" bold="true" box="[1305,1369,1556,1581]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">sp. n.</emphasis>
</taxonomicNameLabel>
(both species with parallel maxillary stylets instead of V-shaped, and males with a single pore plate on sternite VIII). 
<bibRefCitation id="F5374B64FF98FF99D4C5E00B56231A72" box="[151,353,1628,1653]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" refId="ref59180" refString="Maia, V. C., Cardoso, L. J. T. &amp; Braga, J. M. A. (2014) Insect galls from Atlantic Forest areas of Santa Teresa, Espirito Santo, Brazil: characterization and occurrence. Boletim do Museu de Biologia Mello Leitao, 33, 47 - 129." type="journal article">
Maia 
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FF98FF99D485E00A56521A73" box="[215,272,1628,1653]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">et al.</emphasis>
(2014)
</bibRefCitation>
observed this thrips inducing galls in the leaves of an undetermined 
<emphasis id="A3D2EA87FF98FF99D031E00A53F11A72" box="[1123,1203,1629,1652]" italics="true" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Myrcia</emphasis>
species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
